 <br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.worldnuclear.org/focus.cfm?objId=5379A143-564A-44FD-9E8D17467ADEE223">Source.</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
A new report by Finland’s federation of energy industries, Finergy, predicts that the gap between electricity production and consumption in Europe will grow steadily over the next 20 years, leading to ever-increasing reliance on power imports.<br>
<br>
 <br>
The European Electricity Market Outlook report, drafted by a Finergy task force, is a development of the organisation’s Electricity Market 2015 report two years ago, which focused exclusively on Finland and the Nordic region.<br>
 <br>
It takes no stance with regard to energy policy options, but highlights the fact that Europe as a whole will soon have to come to terms with the same supply and demand fundamentals that underpinned Finland’s recent decision to approve the construction of a new nuclear power unit.<br>
<br>
 <br>
The report contains estimates of demand, production and transmission outlook in Finland, Sweden, Norway, Denmark, Germany, France, Great Britain, Italy, the Benelux countries, Russia, Poland and the Baltic states (based largely on current energy policies). It also examines energy-related decision-making within the EU, the global fuel market, and the outlook for electricity production technology. It is currently available (in Finnish only) at Finergy’s Web site (http://www.energia.fi), but will be translated into English at a later date.<br>
 <br>
Specific predictions include: <br>
· Electricity consumption in the countries covered will continue to grow, but slower than previously, with the Baltic countries and Russia showing the fastest growth. Electricity use in Russia decreased by 20% during the 1990s, but future consumption is expected to increase by at least 2% a year, with 1990 levels exceeded again by 2010. Consumption in the Nordic countries will increase from 393 terawatt-hours (TWh) in 2001 to 418 TWh by 2010. <br>
<br>
· Over the next 10 years, between 60 000 and 70 000 megawatts (MW) of additional installed production capacity will be needed in the countries examined. Approximately half of this new capacity will be built in Russia. Over the next 20 years, between 200 000 and 300 000 MW of new capacity will be needed within the current EU area to cover the consumption increase, with the same again needed to compensate for plant closures. <br>
<br>
· Consumption is expected to grow faster than production in several countries, meaning they will become increasingly independent on imports. For example, demand in the Nordic region in 2010 is predicted to exceed supply by about 17 000 TWh in “average” hydro conditions. <br>
<br>
· Gas will be the fastest-growing source, with the UK producing up to 80% of its electricity from gas by 2020. As consumption increases, and production in the North Sea decreases, there will be a “growing need” to import gas from outside the EU. The use of renewable energy sources will continue to grow, with the exception of hydro, but these will mainly “complement” other sources, “even over a perspective of 20 years”. Fossil fuels and nuclear will continue to be major energy sources, but the overall outlook for both is still unclear. <br>
<br>
· If the EU directive proposal on emissions trading is implemented, market prices for electricity are likely to rise “considerably” across the area as a whole. <br>
